{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1773482667535,"sessionID":"ses_3143289ffffebE5N0evuhJd5Hx","part":{"id":"prt_cebcdee0e001pUaNgntrqw0yHC","sessionID":"ses_3143289ffffebE5N0evuhJd5Hx","messageID":"msg_cebcde221001lLg5xOyQhEHLLl","type":"step-start","snapshot":"ad79631b6608fcbb290601e7179a7823bccd9901"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1773482677054,"sessionID":"ses_3143289ffffebE5N0evuhJd5Hx","part":{"id":"prt_cebcdee0f0010wIbMtepeh94mE","sessionID":"ses_3143289ffffebE5N0evuhJd5Hx","messageID":"msg_cebcde221001lLg5xOyQhEHLLl","type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me understand the core task:\n\n**Problem**: When the user quits the TUI while agents are still running (headless mode), then re-opens via `woco resume` or `woco` (TUI), the running agent processes are still alive (PIDs exist), but the ProcessMonitor has no ChildProcess handles for them, so it can't tail their stdout/stderr or detect completion.\n\n**Solution needed**:\n1. In `ProcessMonitor`, add a method to reconnect to running agents by re-attaching to their log files and polling their PIDs for liveness\n2. In `resume.ts`, when an agent's PID is still alive, reconnect to it instead of just \"leaving it alone\" (which means no monitoring)\n3. Detect dead processes and update state accordingly\n\nLet me now implement this:","time":{"start":1773482677053,"end":1773482677053}}}
